title: For Sale:  Early Springfield Armory Mil Spec 1911 A1 45 ACP (uncut ejection port / cross cannons behind ejection port)
postcontent:
For sale is a parkerized Springfield Armory 1911 A1 chambered in 45 ACP. This is one of the earliest evolutions of the mil spec model, as evidenced by the uncut ejection port and the location of the cross cannons behind the ejection port. This particular time period is sought after by collectors and is also considered to be of higher quality than the current production mil specs.

The barrel has been upgraded to a Colt barrel and the trigger feels smoother than stock. I would guess that this gun has had a trigger job at some point, but cannot say for sure because, aside from swapping out the grips, I have made no changes/upgrades to the gun since I have owned it.

The grips are a beautiful cocobolo made from a piece of Brazilian cocobolo driftwood. I can take $40 off of the price if a buyer is not interested in these grips and would prefer black Springfield Armory plastic grips.

I have owned this pistol for about 7 years, during which time it has been fired only a few times (approx. 50 rounds fired); it performed flawlessly each time and there were no malfunctions of any kind. I am not sure what the round count on the pistol was when I took possession of it. It shows signs of use in typical places such as the all too common "idiot mark" and rub marks on the trigger, hammer, grip safety, and mag release. Also, the buyer of this 1911 should be pleased to find that I keep all of my firearms immaculately clean.

Immaculate and unblemished!  This unfired weapon is as new and pristine in condition, and still has factory over-grease seeping from it.  Since leaving the factory in 1989, the breach has only been pulled back three times….. Once by the Action Arms, Ltd. Dealer, once by the previous owner, and once by myself, and there are absolutely no mechanical wear marks on the action to indicate that it ever has been cycled manually or otherwise.  This is truly a collector’s piece of fine weaponry and has been price-reduced to move.

	The “Mini” is more compact but with all the performance of the original UZI Carbine.  The “Mini” uses all of the same magazines as the original UZI Carbine, and delivers the same huge step up in velocity, energy and accuracy compared to a 9mm handgun.

Chambering:		9mm Parabellum
Sights:			Front “post” type
			        Rear “L” flip type, adjustable for 100 meters and 200 meters
Stock:			Metal, left side-folding
Finish:			Black
Barrel Length:		19.8 inches
Length:		        Overall, 35.8 inches
			        Stock Folded, 26.1 inches

The MAS-36 is a short, carbine-style rifle with a two-piece stock and slab-sided receiver. It is chambered for the modern, rimless 7.5x54 French cartridge, a shortened version of the 7.5x57mm MAS mod. 1924 cartridge that had been introduced in 1924 (then modified in 1929), for France's FM 24/29 light machine gun. The rifle was developed based on French experience in World War I and combines various features of other rifles used, like the British SMLE rifle (rear locking lugs resistant to dirt), the US M1917 Enfield rifle (turned down bolt, peep sight), and the German Mauser (five-round box-magazine), to produce an "ugly, roughly made, but immensely strong and reliable" service rifle.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Full case of Federal Auto Match .22LR (TRADE PREFERRED)
location: Beloit Township, south of, Janesville, Wisconsin
postcontent:
Quite a while back, I ordered and only recently received 2 cases of Federal Auto Match. ONLY ONE is for sale/trade. I am keeping the other one for my Ruger 10/22 which eats this stuff like candy. This ammo is terrific for semi-auto rifles and pistols. It's 40 grain bullet and clean burning powder cycle them great without gumming up the action. 
However, I do most of my shooting with a pair of bolt action 22s that actually prefer the cheaper 36 grain copper plated Federal Champion and Remington Golden bullets.
I'll sell the whole case for $400.00, which is FAR CHEAPER than the .19 and .25 cents per round I just saw this stuff listed for from multiple internet retailers, who also charge shipping and handling further raising the price. They also limit the number of boxes you can buy. Incidentally, these were well known retailers and not entities that just popped up for the short term.
I prefer not to sell it, but would rather trade it for Federal Champion 36 grain copper plated 22LR, or I'd even consider trading for Remington Golden Bullets 22LR. That way I won't have to spend the next 6-8 months trying to replace it.
If you want a good 22LR cartridge that will cycle your semi-auto properly without gumming it up, this is it!  Make a trade or buy it outright. (trades preferred)
Trades would be: one box of FEDERAL AUTO MATCH for one box Federal Champion in either the 525 blue or 550 red box. Or, one box of auto match for one 525 round box of Remington Golden bullets 22LR

postcontent:
Not a plain 15-22. This rifle has alot of extra stuff that cost money. I am not by any means asking more than all of it is worth. This was made to be broken down in to just 24'x12' case if preferred. That is just one of 3 configurations (including factory) This is just an opportunity for someone to own a sweet tactical .22 for a HELL of alot less than it would cost to do it themselves. 

Custom Smith & Wesson M&P 15-22 for sale or trade + cash.

This is a very nice .22 AR, and impresses everyone who sees it and handles it.

It is in EXCELLENT condition, and has had 175  rounds put through it, as most all .22's do. If guns were made to wear out after 5000+ rounds it would be worth nothing. Include a lifetime guarantee (doesn't matter how many owners) you can't go wrong.

It comes with:

1. Eotech Green/Red dot sight (%100 eye relief)
2. Magpul MOE adjustable stock
3. Magpul black MOE rubber buttpad
4. Magpul angled foregrip
5. Troy flip sights front and rear (orig m4 sights too)
6. Magpul rail covers (extras included)
7.KINETI-TECH barrel shroud with concave end cap and thread protector
8. GEMTECH .22 barrel extension new (can be also put on the end of Sig Mosquito 22also fully functional brand new)
9.AMMO CCI & Federal .22 lr 850 rnds (700 of which are new & sealed


All of the accessories cost $$$ not including shipping and gunsmith labor.

$650.00 is very fair for what would cost you plenty $$$ to do on your own.

Also comes with 3 25rd mags,Manual, and plano rifle case.

If you want a basic M&P 15-22 for 500, then have at it. If you want a decked out M&P 15-22 that already has tactical upgrades, so you dont have to mess with it, then this is the rifle for you.

This rifle is very accurate. Ejection issues 99% of the time is caused by the large amount of powder residue left from .22 ammo.
You must clean the chamber and the bolt face very thoroughly, in order for the rifle to function properly. This may require cleaning during shooting after a few hundred rounds. Failure to fires are generally caused by residue build-up on the bolt face where the rim of the round seats in the bolt, which keeps the round from seating completely in the bolt, causing the firing pin to not be able to fully strike the rim of the round. 22's are bad for this, as it is a dirty round.

willing to accept decent trades no low balling. As you know cash is king. Must have valid FOID not avail for Chicago or Aurora residents due to the high round capacity.

The assembly process’s final steps include Infused Hard Coat Anodized finish on the alloy, and parkerization on steel surfaces, installation of front and rear sight area picatinny rails.
